<sections><clause id="_the_relation_between_the_numbers_iim_r_and_iib_j" obligation="normative"><title>The relation between the numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> and <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem></title><p id="_1cc2712a-203f-46a3-b2d8-b827ffa70324">In our recent study <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/> on alternate sums of powers of integers, i.e. of sums of the type</p>
<formula id="eq1">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#8484;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>&#8721;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><mi>,</mi><mtext>&#160;with&#160;</mtext><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mi>,</mi><mn>2</mn><mi>,</mi><mo>&#8230;</mo><mi>,</mi></math></stem>
</formula>
<p id="_365c7431-46ae-478b-862f-544020664bc5">it was shown that they can be expressed in the form</p>
<formula id="eq2">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#8484;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>&#8721;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></munderover><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>&#956;</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><mi>,</mi></math></stem>
</formula>
<p id="_9e5ff176-f6dd-44ef-a5d7-4dc9735490af">where <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced open="[" close="]"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></stem> is given by the number of terms in <xref target="eq1"/>, while <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>&#956;</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> are coefficients that have been tabulated.</p>
<p id="_5b647b25-c916-4490-8b3b-edfd22b56a59">We found that these coefficients can be expressed by the &#8220;basic&#8221; integers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&#8801;</mo><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>&#956;</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math></stem>, since</p>
<formula id="eq3">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>&#956;</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></msup><mi>r</mi><mi>!</mi></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mi>!</mi><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>j</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi>!</mi></mrow></mrow></mfrac><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>j</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></msub><mi>,</mi><mtext>&#160;for&#160;</mtext><mi>r</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>j</mi></math></stem>
</formula>
<p id="_8789d3d1-8f4d-47ef-af8e-7a01d18577d5">The alternate sum <xref target="eq1"/>, written in powers of <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math></stem>, thus begins for <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi></math></stem> even with</p>
<formula id="eq4">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#8484;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>&#956;</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>&#8230;</mo><mi>,</mi></math></stem>
</formula>
<p id="_ece51898-d817-4ec1-b7c2-c951109d3642">whereas for <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi></math></stem> odd there is no term proportional to <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math></stem>.</p>
<p id="_56b5760c-d2a6-4a97-9c80-cb807a125d5b">It appears that the numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> play a role similar to that of the well-known Bernoulli numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> which occur in the study of the sums</p>
<formula id="eq5">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&#8801;</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>&#8721;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><mi>.</mi></math></stem>
</formula>
<p id="_347105d7-92ca-463d-990a-d4e8ec9d7147">Some similarities between the numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> and <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> have already been noted in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/>, but it has not been possible to establish a clear link between the two series. It is the purpose of the present Note to make up for this deficiency. Some familiarity with <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/> will make the reading easier.</p>
<p id="_ce12091f-03c5-4603-9582-ca86b84fe7d1">The idea is to use the fact that the numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> are the coefficients of <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math></stem>, as shown in <xref target="eq4"/>. If we can subdivide <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#8484;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> into a sum of contributions of type <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> and determine the coefficients of the linear terms <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math></stem> (in which the Bernoulli numbers occur), it must be possible to obtain the required relation by comparison of the respective coefficients.</p>
<p id="_e5a1f5d4-cfc7-4ffc-be6f-729a4838809f">Let us begin by decomposing the alternate sum <xref target="eq1"/> in a suitable way&#8201;&#8212;&#8201;the very  rearrangement we tried to avoid in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/>. Since <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>n</mi></math></stem> is even, we can put <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>n</mi><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mi>t</mi></math></stem>. Then</p>
<formula id="eq6">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#8484;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>&#8721;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>j</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><mo>&#8722;</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>&#8721;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>j</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup></math></stem>
</formula>
<formula id="_f36ffa3f-a038-41a9-81f1-45b665de68d6" unnumbered="true">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><munderover><mrow><mo>&#8721;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><mo>&#8722;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><munderover><mrow><mo>&#8721;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></munderover><munderover><mrow><mo>&#8721;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>k</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msup></math></stem>
</formula>
<formula id="_d1fd6487-7ded-4996-a362-a40388be7b0b" unnumbered="true">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>&#8721;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>k</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msup><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem>
</formula>
<formula id="_b5027c62-34b0-41b1-b233-e5f052d8614d" unnumbered="true">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8722;</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>&#8721;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>k</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msup><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mi>.</mi></math></stem>
</formula>
<p id="_361689cc-88fc-4c09-9052-fd66870215cb">Let us now look at the development of a Bernoullian sum <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem>. From relation (23) given in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/> we conclude that, for <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8805;</mo><mn>2</mn></math></stem> and even,</p>
<formula id="eq7">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8230;</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>r</mi></mrow></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8230;</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><mi>t</mi><mi>.</mi></math></stem>
</formula>
<p id="_295d994f-3d36-4108-9164-604611857ffd">We note in passing that <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> with <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi></math></stem> odd has no terms proportional to <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math></stem> as the development stops at <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></stem>, exactly as for <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#8484;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem>.</p>
<p id="_94b42e32-105f-41c1-87bb-e8262738c11f">The two cases with <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></stem> and <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></stem> appearing in <xref target="eq6"/> have to be treated separately. One finds</p>
<formula id="eq8">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>t</mi></math></stem>
</formula>
<p id="_f5a8b1a6-dfe6-4b63-8e69-6e8943b70595">and</p>
<formula id="_a7084bd1-300b-4b92-a2b7-0a73b7e29b85" unnumbered="true">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><msup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mi>.</mi></math></stem>
</formula>
<p id="_556942ec-0e7f-4fdf-8be8-381982eb927c">A look at <xref target="eq4"/> shows that the value of <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> can be obtained from <xref target="eq6"/> by assembling the coefficients of <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math></stem> appearing in <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem>. Writing <xref target="eq6"/> as</p>
<formula id="eq9">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#8484;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>&#8721;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>k</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msup><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mi>,</mi></math></stem>
</formula>
<p id="_8ba49c68-3b16-4ff3-815a-5801409b5e44">we find, with <xref target="eq7"/> and <xref target="eq8"/>,</p>
<formula id="eq10">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8722;</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>&#8721;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>j</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem>
</formula>
<formula id="_ce8be240-e895-40f0-a5a0-c59da95bffb2" unnumbered="true">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>&#8721;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mtext>, (even)</mtext></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>j</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mi>,</mi></math></stem>
</formula>
<p id="_aad77b41-5ef9-49ae-9493-4663e09461db">This is the relation looked for. It shows that the two series of numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> and <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> are indeed closely linked, and relation <xref target="eq10"/> is even somewhat reminiscent of the recurrence formula (18) found previously in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/>. It may be worthwhile noting that the sum in <xref target="eq10"/> yields an even integer.</p>
<p id="_8c516014-e575-4498-9b7c-0d8ec6bfd8a3">Let us check (10) with three practical applications.</p>
<ul id="_b05dcda6-4882-40c1-a5f6-0306cfc7e88a">
<li><p id="_4edb11e0-0d0c-4b0b-ab2b-a0c3e3983ad2">For = 8:</p><formula id="_e1da0ccd-0e35-442c-99e2-1d0e99739e13" unnumbered="true">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>&#8721;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>8</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>j</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem>
</formula>
<formula id="_adcd0a0a-09ce-4f03-90a0-e052a0d01754" unnumbered="true">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><mfenced open="[" close="]"><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>8</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>8</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>4</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>8</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>8</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></math></stem>
</formula>
<formula id="_555f6e81-ec90-4de7-a32e-78137b0022a8" unnumbered="true">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><mfenced open="[" close="]"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mn>28</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8722;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mrow><mn>16</mn><mn>70</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>30</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mrow><mn>64</mn><mn>28</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>42</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>17</mn><mi>;</mi></math></stem>
</formula></li>
<li>
<p id="_9663e4be-3f61-41c8-b01f-9a15d5cb08f1">for <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn></math></stem> :</p>
<formula id="_d1b461c0-8421-4c4b-be0e-a382b64b3dda" unnumbered="true">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>&#8721;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>10</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>j</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8230;</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>155</mn><mi>;</mi></math></stem>
</formula>
</li>
<li>
<p id="_723e6091-af3e-4ace-a99d-5d9028ecca9f">for <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn></math></stem> :</p>
<formula id="_fd30b13f-9f71-4762-8fbe-b64d5aacb5ac" unnumbered="true">
<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>11</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>&#8721;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>12</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>j</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8230;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>2</mn><mtext>&#160;</mtext><mn>073</mn></math></stem>
</formula>
</li>
</ul>
<p id="_36cd991a-5aa7-4116-9791-7311e21f2bef">All these results agree with the numerical values given in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/>.</p>
<p id="_32178b85-060d-41b7-8352-77b33a9c65a7">Obviously, the existence of the new relation <xref target="eq10"/> does not me an that the numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> become superfluous; their practical usefulness is obvious in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/>. In any case, <xref target="eq10"/> is a very useful tool for their numerical evaluation, since it is a simple relation making use only of the Bernoulli numbers, which are readily available in tabular form, for example up to <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>60</mn></mrow></msub></math></stem> in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="abramowitz" citeas="[2]"/>.</p></clause>
